{"id":"2005.03786","submitter":"Juan Pablo Borthagaray","authors":"Juan Pablo Borthagaray and Dmitriy Leykekhman and Ricardo H. Nochetto","title":"Local energy estimates for the fractional Laplacian","comments":null,"journal-ref":"SIAM Journal on Numerical Analysis, 59(4), pp. 1918-1947","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA cs.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The integral fractional Laplacian of order $s \\in (0,1)$ is a nonlocal\noperator. It is known that solutions to the Dirichlet problem involving such an\noperator exhibit an algebraic boundary singularity regardless of the domain\nregularity. This, in turn, deteriorates the global regularity of solutions and\nas a result the global convergence rate of the numerical solutions. For finite\nelement discretizations, we derive local error estimates in the $H^s$-seminorm\nand show optimal convergence rates in the interior of the domain by only\nassuming meshes to be shape-regular. These estimates quantify the fact that the\nreduced approximation error is concentrated near the boundary of the domain. We\nillustrate our theoretical results with several numerical examples.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 7 May 2020 22:33:12 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 28 Dec 2022 18:22:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-29"}
